[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Array processing metrics are often assessed in noisy environments.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The model for noise may be either one of spatially incoherent noise, or one with interfering signals following the same propagation physics.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Estimation theory is an important and basic part of signal processing field, which used to deal with estimation problem in which the values of several parameters of the system should be estimated based on measured/empirical data that has a random component.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] As the number of applications increases, estimating temporal and spatial parameters become more important.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Array processing emerged in the last few decades as an active area and was centered on the ability of using and combining data from different sensors (antennas) in order to deal with specific estimation task (spatial and temporal processing).
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] In addition to the information that can be extracted from the collected data the framework uses the advantage prior knowledge about the geometry of the sensor array to perform the estimation task.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Array processing is used in radar, sonar, seismic exploration, anti-jamming and wireless communications.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] One of the main advantages of using array processing along with an array of sensors is a smaller foot-print.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The problems associated with array processing include the number of sources used, their direction of arrivals, and their signal waveforms.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] There are four assumptions in array processing.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The first assumption is that there is uniform propagation in all directions of isotropic and non-dispersive medium.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The second assumption is that for far field array processing, the radius of propagation is much greater than size of the array and that there is plane wave propagation.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The third assumption is that there is a zero mean white noise and signal, which shows uncorrelation.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Finally, the last assumption is that there is no coupling and the calibration is perfect.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The ultimate goal of sensor array signal processing is to estimate the values of parameters by using available temporal and spatial information, collected through sampling a wavefield with a set of antennas that have a precise geometry description.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The processing of the captured data and information is done under the assumption that the wavefield is generated by a finite number of signal sources (emitters), and contains information about signal parameters characterizing and describing the sources.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] There are many applications related to the above problem formulation, where the number of sources, their directions and locations should be specified.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] To motivate the reader, some of the most important applications related to array processing will be discussed.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] array processing concept was closely linked to radar and sonar systems which represent the classical applications of array processing.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The antenna array is used in these systems to determine location(s) of source(s), cancel interference, suppress ground clutter.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] **Radar systems** used basically to detect objects by using radio waves.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The range, altitude, speed and direction of objects can be specified.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Radar systems started as military equipments then entered the civilian world.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] In radar applications, different modes can be used, one of these modes is the active mode.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] In this mode the antenna array based system radiates pulses and listens for the returns.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] By using the returns, the estimation of parameters such as velocity, range and DOAs (direction of arrival) of target of interest become possible.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Using the passive far-field listening arrays, only the DOAs can be estimated.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] **Sonar systems** (Sound Navigation and Ranging) use the sound waves that propagate under the water to detect objects on or under the water surface.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Two types of sonar systems can be defined the active one and the passive one.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] In active sonar, the system emits pulses of sound and listens to the returns that will be used to estimate parameters.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] In the passive sonar, the system is essentially listening for the sounds made by the target objects.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] There is a difference between the radar system that uses radio waves and the sonar system that uses sound waves, the reason why the sonar uses the sound wave is because sound waves travel farther in the water than do radar and light waves.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] In passive sonar, the receiving array has the capability of detecting distant objects and their locations.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Deformable array are usually used in sonar systems where the antenna is typically drawn under the water.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] In active sonar, the sonar system emits sound waves (acoustic energy) then listening and monitoring any existing echo (the reflected waves).
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The reflected sound waves can be used to estimate parameters, such as velocity, position and direction etc.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Difficulties and limitations in sonar systems comparing to radar systems emerged from the fact that the propagation speed of sound waves under the water is slower than the radio waves.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Another source of limitation is the high propagation losses and scattering.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Despite all these limitations and difficulties, sonar system remains a reliable technique for range, distance, position and other parameters estimation for underwater applications.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] NORSAR is an independent geo-scientific research facility that was founded in Norway in 1968.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] NORSAR has been working with array processing ever since to measure seismic activity around the globe.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] They are currently working on an International Monitoring System which will comprise 50 primary and 120 auxiliary seismic stations around the world.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] NORSAR has ongoing work to improve array processing to improve monitoring of seismic activity not only in Norway but around the globe.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Communication can be defined as the process of exchanging of information between two or more parties.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The last two decades witnessed a rapid growth of wireless communication systems.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] This success is a result of advances in communication theory and low power dissipation design process.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] In general, communication (telecommunication) can be done by technological means through either electrical signals (wired communication) or electromagnetic waves (wireless communication).
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Antenna arrays have emerged as a support technology to increase the usage efficiency of spectral and enhance the accuracy of wireless communication systems by utilizing spatial dimension in addition to the classical time and frequency dimensions.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Array processing and estimation techniques have been used in wireless communication.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] During the last decade these techniques were re-explored as ideal candidates to be the solution for numerous problems in wireless communication.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] In wireless communication, problems that affect quality and performance of the system may come from different sources.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The multiuser –medium multiple access- and multipath -signal propagation over multiple scattering paths in wireless channels- communication model is one of the most widespread communication models in wireless communication (mobile communication).
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] In the case of multiuser communication environment, the existence of multiuser increases the inter-user interference possibility that can affect quality and performance of the system adversely.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] In mobile communication systems the multipath problem is one of the basic problems that base stations have to deal with.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Base stations have been using spatial diversity for combating fading due to the severe multipath.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Base stations use an antenna array of several elements to achieve higher selectivity, so called beamforming.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Receiving array can be directed in the direction of one user at a time, while avoiding the interference from other users.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Array processing techniques got on much attention from medical and industrial applications.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] In medical applications, the medical image processing field was one of the basic fields that use array processing.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Other medical applications that use array processing: diseases treatment, tracking waveforms that have information about the condition of internal organs e.g. the heart, localizing and analyzing brain activity by using bio-magnetic sensor arrays.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Speech enhancement and processing represents another field that has been affected by the new era of array processing.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Most of the acoustic front end systems became fully automatic systems (e.g. telephones).
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] However, the operational environment of these systems contains a mix of other acoustic sources; external noises as well as acoustic couplings of loudspeaker signals overwhelm and attenuate the desired speech signal.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] In addition to these external sources, the strength of the desired signal is reduced due to the relatively distance between speaker and microphones.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Array processing techniques have opened new opportunities in speech processing to attenuate noise and echo without degrading the quality of and affecting adversely the speech signal.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] In general array processing techniques can be used in speech processing to reduce the computing power (number of computations) and enhance the quality of the system (the performance).
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Representing the signal as a sum of sub-bands and adapting cancellation filters for the sub-band signals can reduce the demanded computation power and lead to a higher performance system.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Relying on multiple input channels allows designing systems of higher quality comparing to systems that use single channel and solving problems such as source localization, tracking and separation, which cannot be achieved in case of using single channel.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Astronomical environment contains a mix of external signals and noises that affect the quality of the desired signals.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Most of the arrays processing applications in astronomy are related to image processing.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The array used to achieve a higher quality that is not achievable by using a single channel.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The high image quality facilitates quantitative analysis and comparison with images at other wavelengths.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] In general, astronomy arrays can be divided into two classes: the beamforming class and the correlation class.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Correlation arrays provide images over the entire single-element primary beam pattern, computed off-line from records of all the possible correlations between the antennas, pairwise.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] In order to solve this problem (to guarantee that there is a valid solution) do we have to add conditions or assumptions on the operational environment and\or the used model?
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Since there are many parameters used to specify the system like the number of sources, the number of array elements ...etc. are there conditions that should be met first?
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The set of any q steering vectors is linearly independent.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Isotropic and non-dispersive medium – Uniform propagation in all directions.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Zero mean white noise and signal, uncorrelated.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Throughout this survey, it will be assumed that the number of underlying signals, q, in the observed process is considered known.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] There are, however, good and consistent techniques for estimating this value even if it is not known.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] In general, parameters estimation techniques can be classified into: **spectral based and parametric based methods**.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] In the former, one forms some spectrum-like function of the parameter(s) of interest.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The locations of the highest (separated) peaks of the function in question are recorded as the DOA estimates.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Parametric techniques, on the other hand, require a simultaneous search for all parameters of interest.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The basic advantage of using the parametric approach comparing to the spectral based approach is the accuracy, albeit at the expense of an increased computational complexity.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Spectral based algorithmic solutions can be further classified into beamforming techniques and subspace-based techniques.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The first method used to specify and automatically localize the signal sources using antenna arrays was the beamforming technique.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The idea behind beamforming is very simple: steer the array in one direction at a time and measure the output power.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The steering locations where we have the maximum power yield the DOA estimates.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The array response is steered by forming a linear combination of the sensor outputs.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Different beamforming approaches correspond to different choices of the weighting vector **F**.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The advantages of using beamforming technique are the simplicity, easy to use and understand.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] While the disadvantage of using this technique is the low resolution.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Many spectral methods in the past have called upon the spectral decomposition of a covariance matrix to carry out the analysis.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] A breakthrough came about when the eigen-structure of the covariance matrix was explicitly invoked, and its intrinsic properties were directly used to provide a solution to an underlying estimation problem for a given observed process.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] A class of spatial spectral estimation techniques is based on the eigen-value decomposition of the spatial covariance matrix.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The rationale behind this approach is that one wants to emphasize the choices for the steering vector a(θ) which correspond to signal directions.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The method exploits the property that the directions of arrival determine the eigen structure of the matrix.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The tremendous interest in the subspace based methods is mainly due to the introduction of the MUSIC (Multiple Signal Classification) algorithm.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] MUSIC was originally presented as a DOA estimator, then it has been successfully brought back to the spectral analysis/system identification problem with its later development.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] MUSIC spectrum approaches use a single realization of the stochastic process that is represent by the snapshots x (t), t=1, 2 ...M.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] MUSIC estimates are consistent and they converge to true source bearings as the number of snapshots grows to infinity.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] A basic drawback of MUSIC approach is its sensitivity to model errors.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] A costly procedure of calibration is required in MUSIC and it is very sensitive to errors in the calibration procedure.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The cost of calibration increases as the number of parameters that define the array manifold increases.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] While the spectral-based methods presented in the previous section are computationally attractive, they do not always yield sufficient accuracy.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] In particular, for the cases when we have highly correlated signals, the performance of spectral-based methods may be insufficient.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] An alternative is to more fully exploit the underlying data model, leading to so-called parametric array processing methods.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The cost of using such methods to increase the efficiency is that the algorithms typically require a multidimensional search to find the estimates.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The most common used model based approach in signal processing is the maximum likelihood (ML) technique.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] This method requires a statistical framework for the data generation process.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] When applying the ML technique to the array processing problem, two main methods have been considered depending on the signal data model assumption.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] According to the Stochastic ML, the signals are modeled as Gaussian random processes.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] On the other hand, in the Deterministic ML the signals are considered as unknown, deterministic quantities that need to be estimated in conjunction with the direction of arrival.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The stochastic maximum likelihood method is obtained by modeling the signal waveforms as a Gaussian random process under the assumption that the process x(t) is a stationary, zero-mean, Gaussian process that is completely described by its second-order covariance matrix.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] This model is a reasonable one if the measurements are obtained by filtering wide-band signals using a narrow band-pass filter.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] While the background and receiver noise in the assumed data model can be thought of as emanating from a large number of independent noise sources, the same is usually not the case for the emitter signals.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] It therefore appears natural to model the noise as a stationary Gaussian white random process whereas the signal waveforms are deterministic (arbitrary) and unknown.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] According to the Deterministic ML the signals are considered as unknown, deterministic quantities that need to be estimated in conjunction with the direction of arrival.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] This is a natural model for digital communication applications where the signals are far from being normal random variables, and where estimation of the signal is of equal interest.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The problem of computing pairwise correlation as a function of frequency can be solved by two mathematically equivalent but distinct ways.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] By using Discrete Fourier Transform (DFT) it is possible to analyze signals in the time domain as well as in the spectral domain.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The first approach is "XF" correlation because it first cross-correlates antennas (the "X" operation) using a time-domain "lag" convolution, and then computes the spectrum (the "F" operation) for each resulting baseline.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The second approach "FX" takes advantage of the fact that convolution is equivalent to multiplication in Fourier domain.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] It first computes the spectrum for each individual antenna (the F operation), and then multiplies pairwise all antennas for each spectral channel (the X operation).
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] A FX correlator has an advantage over a XF correlators in that the computational complexity is O(N2).
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Therefore, FX correlators are more efficient for larger arrays.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Correlation spectrometers like the Michelson interferometer vary the time lag between signals obtain the power spectrum of input signals.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Cross-correlation spectroscopy with spatial interferometry, is possible by simply substituting a signal with voltage $V_{Y}(t)$ in equation **Eq.II** to produce the cross-correlation $R_{\text{XY}}(\tau )$ and the cross-spectrum $S_{\text{XY}}(f)$ .
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] In radio astronomy, RF interference must be mitigated to detect and observe any meaningful objects and events in the night sky.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] where $\mathbf {R} _{v}$ is the visibilities covariance matrix (sources), $\sigma _{s}^{2}$ is the power of the interferer, and $\sigma _{n}^{2}$ is the noise power, and $\dagger$ denotes the Hermitian transpose.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] One can construct a projection matrix $\mathbf {P} _{a}^{\perp }$ , which, when left and right multiplied by the signal covariance matrix, will reduce the interference term to zero.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Since $\mathbf {a}$ is generally not known, $\mathbf {P} _{a}^{\perp }$ can be constructed using the eigen-decomposition of $\mathbf {R}$ , in particular the matrix containing an orthonormal basis of the noise subspace, which is the orthogonal complement of $\mathbf {a}$ .
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] The disadvantages to this approach include altering the visibilities covariance matrix and coloring the white noise term.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] This scheme attempts to make the interference-plus-noise term spectrally white.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] To do this, left and right multiply $\mathbf {R}$ with inverse square root factors of the interference-plus-noise terms.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] This approach requires much more computationally intensive matrix manipulations, and again the visibilities covariance matrix is altered.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] This scheme requires an accurate estimation of the interference term, but does not alter the noise or sources term.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Array processing technique represents a breakthrough in signal processing.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Many applications and problems which are solvable using array processing techniques are introduced.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] In addition to these applications within the next few years the number of applications that include a form of array signal processing will increase.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] In this article we emphasized the importance of array processing by listing the most important applications that include a form of array processing techniques.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] We briefly describe the different classifications of array processing, spectral and parametric based approaches.
[src:systolic-array/array-processing] Some of the most important algorithms are covered, the advantage(s) and the disadvantage(s) of these algorithms also explained and discussed.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A **convolutional neural network** (**CNN**) is a type of feedforward neural network that learns features via filter (or kernel) optimization.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This type of deep learning network has been applied to process and make predictions from many different types of data including text, images and audio.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are the de-facto standard in deep learning-based approaches to computer vision and image processing, and have only recently been replaced—in some cases—by newer architectures such as the transformer.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Vanishing gradients and exploding gradients, seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks, are prevented by the regularization that comes from using shared weights over fewer connections.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, for *each* neuron in the fully-connected layer, 10,000 weights would be required for processing an image sized 100 × 100 pixels.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, applying cascaded *convolution* (or cross-correlation) kernels, only 25 weights for each convolutional layer are required to process 5x5-sized tiles.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Higher-layer features are extracted from wider context windows, compared to lower-layer features.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are also known as **shift invariant** or **space invariant artificial neural networks**, based on the shared-weight architecture of the convolution kernels or filters that slide along input features and provide translation-equivariant responses known as feature maps.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Counter-intuitively, most convolutional neural networks are not invariant to translation, due to the downsampling operation they apply to the input.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Feedforward neural networks are usually fully connected networks, that is, each neuron in one layer is connected to all neurons in the next layer.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "full connectivity" of these networks makes them prone to overfitting data.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks were inspired by biological processes in that the connectivity pattern between neurons resembles the organization of the animal visual cortex.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Individual cortical neurons respond to stimuli only in a restricted region of the visual field known as the receptive field.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The receptive fields of different neurons partially overlap such that they cover the entire visual field.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use relatively little pre-processing compared to other image classification algorithms.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This means that the network learns to optimize the filters (or kernels) through automated learning, whereas in traditional algorithms these filters are hand-engineered.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This simplifies and automates the process, enhancing efficiency and scalability overcoming human-intervention bottlenecks.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A convolutional neural network consists of an input layer, hidden layers and an output layer.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional neural network, the hidden layers include one or more layers that perform convolutions.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typically this includes a layer that performs a dot product of the convolution kernel with the layer's input matrix.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This product is usually the Frobenius inner product, and its activation function is commonly ReLU.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As the convolution kernel slides along the input matrix for the layer, the convolution operation generates a feature map, which in turn contributes to the input of the next layer.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is followed by other layers such as pooling layers, fully connected layers, and normalization layers.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Here it should be noted how close a convolutional neural network is to a matched filter.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (number of inputs) × (feature map height) × (feature map width) × (feature map channels).
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional layers convolve the input and pass its result to the next layer.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to the response of a neuron in the visual cortex to a specific stimulus.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each convolutional neuron processes data only for its receptive field.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although fully connected feedforward neural networks can be used to learn features and classify data, this architecture is generally impractical for larger inputs (e.g., high-resolution images), which would require massive numbers of neurons because each pixel is a relevant input feature.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A fully connected layer for an image of size 100 × 100 has 10,000 weights for *each* neuron in the second layer.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution reduces the number of free parameters, allowing the network to be deeper.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, using a 5 × 5 tiling region, each with the same shared weights, requires only 25 neurons.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using shared weights means there are many fewer parameters, which helps avoid the vanishing gradients and exploding gradients problems seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To speed processing, standard convolutional layers can be replaced by depthwise separable convolutional layers, which are based on a depthwise convolution followed by a pointwise convolution.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The *depthwise convolution* is a spatial convolution applied independently over each channel of the input tensor, while the *pointwise convolution* is a standard convolution restricted to the use of $1\times 1$ kernels.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks may include local and/or global pooling layers along with traditional convolutional layers.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling layers reduce the dimensions of data by combining the outputs of neuron clusters at one layer into a single neuron in the next layer.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Local pooling combines small clusters, tiling sizes such as 2 × 2 are commonly used.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Global pooling acts on all the neurons of the feature map.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are two common types of pooling in popular use: max and average.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] *Max pooling* uses the maximum value of each local cluster of neurons in the feature map, while *average pooling* takes the average value.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fully connected layers connect every neuron in one layer to every neuron in another layer.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the same as a traditional multilayer perceptron neural network (MLP).
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in the fully connected layer receives input from all the neurons in the previous layer.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These inputs are weighted and summed with the corresponding biases, and then passed through an activation function to perform a nonlinear transformation, generating the output.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The flattened matrix goes through a fully connected layer to classify the images.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In neural networks, each neuron receives input from some number of locations in the previous layer.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional layer, each neuron receives input from only a restricted area of the previous layer called the neuron's *receptive field*.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Whereas, in a fully connected layer, the receptive field is the *entire previous layer*.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, in each convolutional layer, each neuron takes input from a larger area in the input than previous layers.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is due to applying the convolution over and over, which takes the value of a pixel into account, as well as its surrounding pixels.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When using dilated layers, the number of pixels in the receptive field remains constant, but the field is more sparsely populated as its dimensions grow when combining the effect of several layers.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To manipulate the receptive field size as desired, there are some alternatives to the standard convolutional layer.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, atrous or dilated convolution expands the receptive field size without increasing the number of parameters by interleaving visible and blind regions.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Moreover, a single dilated convolutional layer can comprise filters with multiple dilation ratios, thus having a variable receptive field size.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in a neural network computes an output value by applying a specific function to the input values received from the receptive field in the previous layer.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The function that is applied to the input values is determined by a vector of weights and a bias (typically real numbers).
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning consists of iteratively adjusting these biases and weights.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The vectors of weights and biases are called *filters* and represent particular features of the input (e.g., a particular shape).
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A distinguishing feature of CNNs is that many neurons can share the same filter.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces the memory footprint because a single bias and a single vector of weights are used across all receptive fields that share that filter, as opposed to each receptive field having its own bias and vector weighting.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional neural network is essentially the reverse of a CNN.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It consists of deconvolutional layers and unpooling layers.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional layer is the transpose of a convolutional layer.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Specifically, a convolutional layer can be written as a multiplication with a matrix, and a deconvolutional layer is multiplication with the transpose of that matrix.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The max-unpooling layer is the simplest, as it simply copies each entry multiple times.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a 2-by-2 max-unpooling layer is $[x]\mapsto {\begin{bmatrix}x&x\\x&x\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Deconvolution layers are used in image generators.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By default, it creates periodic checkerboard artifact, which can be fixed by upscale-then-convolve.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNN are often compared to the way the brain achieves vision processing in living organisms.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Work by Hubel and Wiesel in the 1950s and 1960s showed that cat visual cortices contain neurons that individually respond to small regions of the visual field.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Provided the eyes are not moving, the region of visual space within which visual stimuli affect the firing of a single neuron is known as its receptive field.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neighboring cells have similar and overlapping receptive fields.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Receptive field size and location varies systematically across the cortex to form a complete map of visual space.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The cortex in each hemisphere represents the contralateral visual field.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hubel and Wiesel also proposed a cascading model of these two types of cells for use in pattern recognition tasks.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same paper, Fukushima also introduced the ReLU (rectified linear unit) activation function.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "neocognitron" was introduced by Fukushima in 1980.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Several supervised and unsupervised learning algorithms have been proposed over the decades to train the weights of a neocognitron.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Today, however, the CNN architecture is usually trained through backpropagation.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fukushima's ReLU activation function was not used in his neocognitron since all the weights were nonnegative; lateral inhibition was used instead.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The rectifier has become a very popular activation function for CNNs and deep neural networks in general.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The term "convolution" first appears in neural networks in a paper by Toshiteru Homma, Les Atlas, and Robert Marks II at the first Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems in 1987.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their paper replaced multiplication with convolution in time, inherently providing shift invariance, motivated by and connecting more directly to the signal-processing concept of a filter, and demonstrated it on a speech recognition task.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They also pointed out that as a data-trainable system, convolution is essentially equivalent to correlation since reversal of the weights does not affect the final learned function ("For convenience, we denote * as correlation instead of convolution.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that convolving a(t) with b(t) is equivalent to correlating a(-t) with b(t).").
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Modern CNN implementations typically do correlation and call it convolution, for convenience, as they did here.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel et al. for phoneme recognition and was an early convolutional network exhibiting shift-invariance.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A TDNN is a 1-D convolutional neural net where the convolution is performed along the time axis of the data.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the first CNN utilizing weight sharing in combination with a training by gradient descent, using backpropagation.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, while also using a pyramidal structure as in the neocognitron, it performed a global optimization of the weights instead of a local one.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs are convolutional networks that share weights along the temporal dimension.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They allow speech signals to be processed time-invariantly.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Hampshire and Waibel introduced a variant that performs a two-dimensional convolution.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since these TDNNs operated on spectrograms, the resulting phoneme recognition system was invariant to both time and frequency shifts, as with images processed by a neocognitron.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs improved the performance of far-distance speech recognition.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) designed a 2-D CNN system to recognize hand-written ZIP Code numbers.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the lack of an efficient training method to determine the kernel coefficients of the involved convolutions meant that all the coefficients had to be laboriously hand-designed.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Following the advances in the training of 1-D CNNs by Waibel et al.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) used back-propagation to learn the convolution kernel coefficients directly from images of hand-written numbers.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning was thus fully automatic, performed better than manual coefficient design, and was suited to a broader range of image recognition problems and image types.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1988) used back-propagation to train the convolution kernels of a CNN for alphabets recognition.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was called shift-invariant pattern recognition neural network before the name CNN was coined later in the early 1990s.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Wei Zhang et al. also applied the same CNN without the last fully connected layer for medical image object segmentation (1991) and breast cancer detection in mammograms (1994).
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach became a foundation of modern computer vision.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Yamaguchi et al. introduced the concept of max pooling, a fixed filtering operation that calculates and propagates the maximum value of a given region.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They did so by combining TDNNs with max pooling to realize a speaker-independent isolated word recognition system.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In their system they used several TDNNs per word, one for each syllable.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The results of each TDNN over the input signal were combined using max pooling and the outputs of the pooling layers were then passed on to networks performing the actual word classification.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a variant of the neocognitron called the *cresceptron*, instead of using Fukushima's spatial averaging with inhibition and saturation, J.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weng et al. in 1993 used max pooling, where a downsampling unit computes the maximum of the activations of the units in its patch, introducing this method into the vision field.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is often used in modern CNNs.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] LeNet-5, a pioneering 7-level convolutional network by LeCun et al. in 1995, classifies hand-written numbers on checks digitized in 32×32 pixel images.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The ability to process higher-resolution images requires larger and more layers of convolutional neural networks, so this technique is constrained by the availability of computing resources.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was superior than other commercial courtesy amount reading systems (as of 1995).
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The system was integrated in NCR's check reading systems, and fielded in several American banks since June 1996, reading millions of checks per day.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A shift-invariant neural network was proposed by Wei Zhang et al. for image character recognition in 1988.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is a modified Neocognitron by keeping only the convolutional interconnections between the image feature layers and the last fully connected layer.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was trained with back-propagation.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The training algorithm was further improved in 1991 to improve its generalization ability.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model architecture was modified by removing the last fully connected layer and applied for medical image segmentation (1991) and automatic detection of breast cancer in mammograms (1994).
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A different convolution-based design was proposed in 1988 for application to decomposition of one-dimensional electromyography convolved signals via de-convolution.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This design was modified in 1989 to other de-convolution-based designs.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although CNNs were invented in the 1980s, their breakthrough in the 2000s required fast implementations on graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Jung that standard neural networks can be greatly accelerated on GPUs.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 20 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2005, another paper also emphasised the value of GPGPU for machine learning.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The first GPU-implementation of a CNN was described in 2006 by K.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 4 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same period, GPUs were also used for unsupervised training of deep belief networks.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2010, Dan Ciresan et al. at IDSIA trained deep feedforward networks on GPUs.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, they extended this to CNNs, accelerating by 60 compared to training CPU.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, the network won an image recognition contest where they achieved superhuman performance for the first time.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Then they won more competitions and achieved state of the art on several benchmarks.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Subsequently, AlexNet, a similar GPU-based CNN by Alex Krizhevsky et al. won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was an early catalytic event for the AI boom.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Compared to the training of CNNs using GPUs, not much attention was given to CPU.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (Viebke et al 2019) parallelizes CNN by thread- and SIMD-level parallelism that is available on the Intel Xeon Phi.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the past, traditional multilayer perceptron (MLP) models were used for image recognition.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the full connectivity between nodes caused the curse of dimensionality, and was computationally intractable with higher-resolution images.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A 1000×1000-pixel image with RGB color channels has 3 million weights per fully-connected neuron, which is too high to feasibly process efficiently at scale.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, in CIFAR-10, images are only of size 32×32×3 (32 wide, 32 high, 3 color channels), so a single fully connected neuron in the first hidden layer of a regular neural network would have 32*32*3 = 3,072 weights.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Also, such network architecture does not take into account the spatial structure of data, treating input pixels which are far apart in the same way as pixels that are close together.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This ignores locality of reference in data with a grid-topology (such as images), both computationally and semantically.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, full connectivity of neurons is wasteful for purposes such as image recognition that are dominated by spatially local input patterns.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional neural networks are variants of multilayer perceptrons, designed to emulate the behavior of a visual cortex.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These models mitigate the challenges posed by the MLP architecture by exploiting the strong spatially local correlation present in natural images.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Together, these properties allow CNNs to achieve better generalization on vision problems.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weight sharing dramatically reduces the number of free parameters learned, thus lowering the memory requirements for running the network and allowing the training of larger, more powerful networks.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A CNN architecture is formed by a stack of distinct layers that transform the input volume into an output volume (e.g. holding the class scores) through a differentiable function.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A few distinct types of layers are commonly used.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The convolutional layer is the core building block of a CNN.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The layer's parameters consist of a set of learnable filters (or kernels), which have a small receptive field, but extend through the full depth of the input volume.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] During the forward pass, each filter is convolved across the width and height of the input volume, computing the dot product between the filter entries and the input, producing a 2-dimensional activation map of that filter.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As a result, the network learns filters that activate when it detects some specific type of feature at some spatial position in the input.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Stacking the activation maps for all filters along the depth dimension forms the full output volume of the convolution layer.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Every entry in the output volume can thus also be interpreted as an output of a neuron that looks at a small region in the input.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each entry in an activation map use the same set of parameters that define the filter.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning has been adapted for use in convolutional layers by using sparse patches with a high-mask ratio and a global response normalization layer.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When dealing with high-dimensional inputs such as images, it is impractical to connect neurons to all neurons in the previous volume because such a network architecture does not take the spatial structure of the data into account.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks exploit spatially local correlation by enforcing a sparse local connectivity pattern between neurons of adjacent layers: each neuron is connected to only a small region of the input volume.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The extent of this connectivity is a hyperparameter called the receptive field of the neuron.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The connections are local in space (along width and height), but always extend along the entire depth of the input volume.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Such an architecture ensures that the learned filters produce the strongest response to a spatially local input pattern.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The spatial size of the output volume is a function of the input volume size W , the kernel field size K of the convolutional layer neurons, the stride S , and the amount of zero padding P on the border.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] If this number is not an integer, then the strides are incorrect and the neurons cannot be tiled to fit across the input volume in a symmetric way.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In general, setting zero padding to be ${\textstyle P=(K-1)/2}$ when the stride is $S=1$ ensures that the input volume and output volume will have the same size spatially.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, it is not always completely necessary to use all of the neurons of the previous layer.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a neural network designer may decide to use just a portion of padding.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A parameter sharing scheme is used in convolutional layers to control the number of free parameters.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It relies on the assumption that if a patch feature is useful to compute at some spatial position, then it should also be useful to compute at other positions.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Denoting a single 2-dimensional slice of depth as a *depth slice*, the neurons in each depth slice are constrained to use the same weights and bias.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since all neurons in a single depth slice share the same parameters, the forward pass in each depth slice of the convolutional layer can be computed as a convolution of the neuron's weights with the input volume.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Therefore, it is common to refer to the sets of weights as a filter (or a kernel), which is convolved with the input.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The result of this convolution is an activation map, and the set of activation maps for each different filter are stacked together along the depth dimension to produce the output volume.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Parameter sharing contributes to the translation invariance of the CNN architecture.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sometimes, the parameter sharing assumption may not make sense.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is especially the case when the input images to a CNN have some specific centered structure; for which we expect completely different features to be learned on different spatial locations.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One practical example is when the inputs are faces that have been centered in the image: we might expect different eye-specific or hair-specific features to be learned in different parts of the image.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In that case it is common to relax the parameter sharing scheme, and instead simply call the layer a "locally connected layer".
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In this layer, the convolutional kernels' parameters are not shared.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Instead, the network learns independent weights and biases for each spatial location.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This allows each location to have its own feature-learning ability, making it better suited to handle images with distinct central structures or irregular features.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another important concept of CNNs is pooling, which is used as a form of non-linear down-sampling.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling provides downsampling because it reduces the spatial dimensions (height and width) of the input feature maps while retaining the most important information.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are several non-linear functions to implement pooling, where *max pooling* and *average pooling* are the most common.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling aggregates information from small regions of the input creating partitions of the input feature map, typically using a fixed-size window (like 2x2) and applying a stride (often 2) to move the window across the input.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that without using a stride greater than 1, pooling would not perform downsampling, as it would simply move the pooling window across the input one step at a time, without reducing the size of the feature map.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the stride is what actually causes the downsampling by determining how much the pooling window moves over the input.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Intuitively, the exact location of a feature is less important than its rough location relative to other features.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the idea behind the use of pooling in convolutional neural networks.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer serves to progressively reduce the spatial size of the representation, to reduce the number of parameters, memory footprint and amount of computation in the network, and hence to also control overfitting.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is common to periodically insert a pooling layer between successive convolutional layers (each one typically followed by an activation function, such as a ReLU layer) in a CNN architecture.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] While pooling layers contribute to local translation invariance, they do not provide global translation invariance in a CNN, unless a form of global pooling is used.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer commonly operates independently on every depth, or slice, of the input and resizes it spatially.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The depth dimension remains unchanged (this is true for other forms of pooling as well).
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In addition to max pooling, pooling units can use other functions, such as average pooling or ℓ2-norm pooling.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Average pooling was often used historically but has recently fallen out of favor compared to max pooling, which generally performs better in practice.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to the effects of fast spatial reduction of the size of the representation, there is a recent trend towards using smaller filters or discarding pooling layers altogether.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A channel max pooling (CMP) operation layer conducts the MP operation along the channel side among the corresponding positions of the consecutive feature maps for the purpose of redundant information elimination.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The CMP makes the significant features gather together within fewer channels, which is important for fine-grained image classification that needs more discriminating features.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Meanwhile, another advantage of the CMP operation is to make the channel number of feature maps smaller before it connects to the first fully connected (FC) layer.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Similar to the MP operation, we denote the input feature maps and output feature maps of a CMP layer as F ∈ R(C×M×N) and C ∈ R(c×M×N), respectively, where C and c are the channel numbers of the input and output feature maps, M and N are the widths and the height of the feature maps, respectively.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that the CMP operation only changes the channel number of the feature maps.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The width and the height of the feature maps are not changed, which is different from the MP operation.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is the abbreviation of rectified linear unit.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was proposed by Alston Householder in 1941, and used in CNN by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1969.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU applies the non-saturating activation function ${\textstyle f(x)=\max(0,x)}$ .
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It effectively removes negative values from an activation map by setting them to zero.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It introduces nonlinearity to the decision function and in the overall network without affecting the receptive fields of the convolution layers.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, Xavier Glorot, Antoine Bordes and Yoshua Bengio found that ReLU enables better training of deeper networks, compared to widely used activation functions prior to 2011.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other functions can also be used to increase nonlinearity, for example the saturating hyperbolic tangent $f(x)=\tanh(x)$ , $f(x)=|\tanh(x)|$ , and the sigmoid function ${\textstyle \sigma (x)=(1+e^{-x})^{-1}}$ .
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is often preferred to other functions because it trains the neural network several times faster without a significant penalty to generalization accuracy.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] After several convolutional and max pooling layers, the final classification is done via fully connected layers.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neurons in a fully connected layer have connections to all activations in the previous layer, as seen in regular (non-convolutional) artificial neural networks.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their activations can thus be computed as an affine transformation, with matrix multiplication followed by a bias offset (vector addition of a learned or fixed bias term).
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "loss layer", or "loss function", exemplifies how training penalizes the deviation between the predicted output of the network, and the true data labels (during supervised learning).
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Various loss functions can be used, depending on the specific task.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The Softmax loss function is used for predicting a single class of *K* mutually exclusive classes.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sigmoid cross-entropy loss is used for predicting *K* independent probability values in $[0,1]$ .
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Euclidean loss is used for regressing to real-valued labels $(-\infty ,\infty )$ .
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hyperparameters are various settings that are used to control the learning process.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use more hyperparameters than a standard multilayer perceptron (MLP).
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Padding is the addition of (typically) 0-valued pixels on the borders of an image.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is done so that the border pixels are not undervalued (lost) from the output because they would ordinarily participate in only a single receptive field instance.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The padding applied is typically one less than the corresponding kernel dimension.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a convolutional layer using 3x3 kernels would receive a 2-pixel pad, that is 1 pixel on each side of the image.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The stride is the number of pixels that the analysis window moves on each iteration.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A stride of 2 means that each kernel is offset by 2 pixels from its predecessor.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since feature map size decreases with depth, layers near the input layer tend to have fewer filters while higher layers can have more.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To equalize computation at each layer, the product of feature values *va* with pixel position is kept roughly constant across layers.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Preserving more information about the input would require keeping the total number of activations (number of feature maps times number of pixel positions) non-decreasing from one layer to the next.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The number of feature maps directly controls the capacity and depends on the number of available examples and task complexity.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Common filter sizes found in the literature vary greatly, and are usually chosen based on the data set.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typical filter sizes range from 1x1 to 7x7.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As two famous examples, AlexNet used 3x3, 5x5, and 11x11.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The challenge is to find the right level of granularity so as to create abstractions at the proper scale, given a particular data set, and without overfitting.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is typically used, often with a 2x2 dimension.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This implies that the input is drastically downsampled, reducing processing cost.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Greater pooling reduces the dimension of the signal, and may result in unacceptable information loss.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Often, non-overlapping pooling windows perform best.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Dilation involves ignoring pixels within a kernel.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces processing memory potentially without significant signal loss.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A dilation of 2 on a 3x3 kernel expands the kernel to 5x5, while still processing 9 (evenly spaced) pixels.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Accordingly, dilation of 4 expands the kernel to 7x7.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is commonly assumed that CNNs are invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution or pooling layers within a CNN that do not have a stride greater than one are indeed equivariant to translations of the input.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Furthermore, if a CNN makes use of fully connected layers, translation equivariance does not imply translation invariance, as the fully connected layers are not invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One solution for complete translation invariance is avoiding any down-sampling throughout the network and applying global average pooling at the last layer.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Additionally, several other partial solutions have been proposed, such as anti-aliasing before downsampling operations, spatial transformer networks, data augmentation, subsampling combined with pooling, and capsule neural networks.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The accuracy of the final model is typically estimated on a sub-part of the dataset set apart at the start, often called a test set.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Alternatively, methods such as *k*-fold cross-validation are applied.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other strategies include using conformal prediction.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Regularization is a process of introducing additional information to solve an ill-posed problem or to prevent overfitting.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use various types of regularization.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because networks have so many parameters, they are prone to overfitting.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One method to reduce overfitting is dropout, introduced in 2014.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At each training stage, individual nodes are either "dropped out" of the net (ignored) with probability $1-p$ or kept with probability p , so that a reduced network is left; incoming and outgoing edges to a dropped-out node are also removed.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Only the reduced network is trained on the data in that stage.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The removed nodes are then reinserted into the network with their original weights.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the training stages, p is usually 0.5; for input nodes, it is typically much higher because information is directly lost when input nodes are ignored.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At testing time after training has finished, we would ideally like to find a sample average of all possible $2^{n}$ dropped-out networks; unfortunately this is unfeasible for large values of n .
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, we can find an approximation by using the full network with each node's output weighted by a factor of p , so the expected value of the output of any node is the same as in the training stages.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the biggest contribution of the dropout method: although it effectively generates $2^{n}$ neural nets, and as such allows for model combination, at test time only a single network needs to be tested.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By avoiding training all nodes on all training data, dropout decreases overfitting.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The method also significantly improves training speed.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This makes the model combination practical, even for deep neural networks.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The technique seems to reduce node interactions, leading them to learn more robust features that better generalize to new data.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is the generalization of dropout in which each connection, rather than each output unit, can be dropped with probability $1-p$ .
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each unit thus receives input from a random subset of units in the previous layer.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is similar to dropout as it introduces dynamic sparsity within the model, but differs in that the sparsity is on the weights, rather than the output vectors of a layer.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the fully connected layer with DropConnect becomes a sparsely connected layer in which the connections are chosen at random during the training stage.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A major drawback to dropout is that it does not have the same benefits for convolutional layers, where the neurons are not fully connected.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach is free of hyperparameters and can be combined with other regularization approaches, such as dropout and data augmentation.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] An alternate view of stochastic pooling is that it is equivalent to standard max pooling but with many copies of an input image, each having small local deformations.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to explicit elastic deformations of the input images, which delivers excellent performance on the MNIST data set.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using stochastic pooling in a multilayer model gives an exponential number of deformations since the selections in higher layers are independent of those below.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because the degree of model overfitting is determined by both its power and the amount of training it receives, providing a convolutional network with more training examples can reduce overfitting.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because there is often not enough available data to train, especially considering that some part should be spared for later testing, two approaches are to either generate new data from scratch (if possible) or perturb existing data to create new ones.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, input images can be cropped, rotated, or rescaled to create new examples with the same labels as the original training set.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One of the simplest methods to prevent overfitting of a network is to simply stop the training before overfitting has had a chance to occur.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It comes with the disadvantage that the learning process is halted.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another simple way to prevent overfitting is to limit the number of parameters, typically by limiting the number of hidden units in each layer or limiting network depth.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For convolutional networks, the filter size also affects the number of parameters.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Limiting the number of parameters restricts the predictive power of the network directly, reducing the complexity of the function that it can perform on the data, and thus limits the amount of overfitting.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A simple form of added regularizer is weight decay, which simply adds an additional error, proportional to the sum of weights (L1 norm) or squared magnitude (L2 norm) of the weight vector, to the error at each node.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The level of acceptable model complexity can be reduced by increasing the proportionality constant('alpha' hyperparameter), thus increasing the penalty for large weight vectors.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L2 regularization is the most common form of regularization.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It can be implemented by penalizing the squared magnitude of all parameters directly in the objective.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The L2 regularization has the intuitive interpretation of heavily penalizing peaky weight vectors and preferring diffuse weight vectors.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to multiplicative interactions between weights and inputs this has the useful property of encouraging the network to use all of its inputs a little rather than some of its inputs a lot.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It makes the weight vectors sparse during optimization.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, neurons with L1 regularization end up using only a sparse subset of their most important inputs and become nearly invariant to the noisy inputs.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L1 with L2 regularization can be combined; this is called elastic net regularization.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another form of regularization is to enforce an absolute upper bound on the magnitude of the weight vector for every neuron and use projected gradient descent to enforce the constraint.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In practice, this corresponds to performing the parameter update as normal, and then enforcing the constraint by clamping the weight vector ${\vec {w}}$ of every neuron to satisfy $\|{\vec {w}}\|_{2}<c$ .
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Some papers report improvements when using this form of regularization.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Pooling loses the precise spatial relationships between high-level parts (such as nose and mouth in a face image).
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] These relationships are needed for identity recognition.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Overlapping the pools so that each feature occurs in multiple pools, helps retain the information.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Translation alone cannot extrapolate the understanding of geometric relationships to a radically new viewpoint, such as a different orientation or scale.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] On the other hand, people are very good at extrapolating; after seeing a new shape once they can recognize it from a different viewpoint.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] An earlier common way to deal with this problem is to train the network on transformed data in different orientations, scales, lighting, etc. so that the network can cope with these variations.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is computationally intensive for large data-sets.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The alternative is to use a hierarchy of coordinate frames and use a group of neurons to represent a conjunction of the shape of the feature and its pose relative to the retina.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The pose relative to the retina is the relationship between the coordinate frame of the retina and the intrinsic features' coordinate frame.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Thus, one way to represent something is to embed the coordinate frame within it.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This allows large features to be recognized by using the consistency of the poses of their parts (e.g. nose and mouth poses make a consistent prediction of the pose of the whole face).
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This approach ensures that the higher-level entity (e.g. face) is present when the lower-level (e.g. nose and mouth) agree on its prediction of the pose.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The vectors of neuronal activity that represent pose ("pose vectors") allow spatial transformations modeled as linear operations that make it easier for the network to learn the hierarchy of visual entities and generalize across viewpoints.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is similar to the way the human visual system imposes coordinate frames in order to represent shapes.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs are often used in image recognition systems.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2012, an error rate of 0.23% on the MNIST database was reported.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper on using CNN for image classification reported that the learning process was "surprisingly fast"; in the same paper, the best published results as of 2011 were achieved in the MNIST database and the NORB database.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, a similar CNN called AlexNet won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] When applied to facial recognition, CNNs achieved a large decrease in error rate.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper reported a 97.6% recognition rate on "5,600 still images of more than 10 subjects".
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs were used to assess video quality in an objective way after manual training; the resulting system had a very low root mean square error.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and hundreds of object classes.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In the ILSVRC 2014, a large-scale visual recognition challenge, almost every highly ranked team used CNN as their basic framework.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The winner GoogLeNet (the foundation of DeepDream) increased the mean average precision of object detection to 0.439329, and reduced classification error to 0.06656, the best result to date.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its network applied more than 30 layers.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] That performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests was close to that of humans.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on a stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters, an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] By contrast, those kinds of images rarely trouble humans.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Humans, however, tend to have trouble with other issues.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained categories such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, a many-layered CNN demonstrated the ability to spot faces from a wide range of angles, including upside down, even when partially occluded, with competitive performance.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The network was trained on a database of 200,000 images that included faces at various angles and orientations and a further 20 million images without faces.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They used batches of 128 images over 50,000 iterations.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to image data domains, there is relatively little work on applying CNNs to video classification.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Video is more complex than images since it has another (temporal) dimension.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, some extensions of CNNs into the video domain have been explored.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] One approach is to treat space and time as equivalent dimensions of the input and perform convolutions in both time and space.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another way is to fuse the features of two convolutional neural networks, one for the spatial and one for the temporal stream.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Long short-term memory (LSTM) recurrent units are typically incorporated after the CNN to account for inter-frame or inter-clip dependencies.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unsupervised learning schemes for training spatio-temporal features have been introduced, based on convolutional gated restricted Boltzmann machines and independent subspace analysis.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its application can be seen in text-to-video models.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have also been explored for natural language processing.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNN models are effective for various NLP problems and achieved excellent results in semantic parsing, search query retrieval, sentence modeling, classification, prediction and other traditional NLP tasks.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to traditional language processing methods such as recurrent neural networks, CNNs can represent different contextual realities of language that do not rely on a series-sequence assumption, while RNNs are better suitable when classical time series modeling is required.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been applied in ecological and behavioral research to automatically detect and quantify animal behavior from visual data, enabling identification of animals, tracking of individuals, estimation of pose, and classification of specific actions such as feeding, and social interactions.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Combined with multi-object tracking and temporal modeling, these systems can extract behavioral sequences over extended recordings, reducing reliance on manual annotation and increasing throughput for studies of individual variation, social networks, and collective dynamics.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A CNN with 1-D convolutions was used on time series in the frequency domain (spectral residual) by an unsupervised model to detect anomalies in the time domain.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Predicting the interaction between molecules and biological proteins can identify potential treatments.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, Atomwise introduced AtomNet, the first deep learning neural network for structure-based drug design.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The system trains directly on 3-dimensional representations of chemical interactions.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Similar to how image recognition networks learn to compose smaller, spatially proximate features into larger, complex structures, AtomNet discovers chemical features, such as aromaticity, sp3 carbons, and hydrogen bonding.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, AtomNet was used to predict novel candidate biomolecules for multiple disease targets, most notably treatments for the Ebola virus and multiple sclerosis.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been used in the game of checkers.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] From 1999 to 2001, Fogel and Chellapilla published papers showing how a convolutional neural network could learn to play checkers using co-evolution.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The learning process did not use prior human professional games, but rather focused on a minimal set of information contained in the checkerboard: the location and type of pieces, and the difference in number of pieces between the two sides.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Ultimately, the program (Blondie24) was tested on 165 games against players and ranked in the highest 0.4%.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] It also earned a win against the program Chinook at its "expert" level of play.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In December 2014, Clark and Storkey published a paper showing that a CNN trained by supervised learning from a database of human professional games could outperform GNU Go and win some games against Monte Carlo tree search Fuego 1.1 in a fraction of the time it took Fuego to play.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Later it was announced that a large 12-layer convolutional neural network had correctly predicted the professional move in 55% of positions, equalling the accuracy of a 6 dan human player.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A couple of CNNs for choosing moves to try ("policy network") and evaluating positions ("value network") driving MCTS were used by AlphaGo, the first to beat the best human player at the time.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Recurrent neural networks are generally considered the best neural network architectures for time series forecasting (and sequence modeling in general), but recent studies show that convolutional networks can perform comparably or even better.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Dilated convolutions might enable one-dimensional convolutional neural networks to effectively learn time series dependences.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutions can be implemented more efficiently than RNN-based solutions, and they do not suffer from vanishing (or exploding) gradients.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional networks can provide an improved forecasting performance when there are multiple similar time series to learn from.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs can also be applied to further tasks in time series analysis (e.g., time series classification or quantile forecasting).
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] As archaeological findings such as clay tablets with cuneiform writing are increasingly acquired using 3D scanners, benchmark datasets are becoming available, including *HeiCuBeDa* providing almost 2000 normalized 2-D and 3-D datasets prepared with the GigaMesh Software Framework.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] So curvature-based measures are used in conjunction with geometric neural networks (GNNs), e.g. for period classification of those clay tablets being among the oldest documents of human history.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For many applications, training data is not very available.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional neural networks usually require a large amount of training data in order to avoid overfitting.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A common technique is to train the network on a larger data set from a related domain.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Once the network parameters have converged an additional training step is performed using the in-domain data to fine-tune the network weights, this is known as transfer learning.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Furthermore, this technique allows convolutional network architectures to successfully be applied to problems with tiny training sets.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] End-to-end training and prediction are common practice in computer vision.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, human interpretable explanations are required for critical systems such as self-driving cars.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] With recent advances in visual salience, spatial attention, and temporal attention, the most critical spatial regions/temporal instants could be visualized to justify the CNN predictions.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A deep Q-network (DQN) is a type of deep learning model that combines a deep neural network with Q-learning, a form of reinforcement learning.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unlike earlier reinforcement learning agents, DQNs that utilize CNNs can learn directly from high-dimensional sensory inputs via reinforcement learning.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Preliminary results were presented in 2014, with an accompanying paper in February 2015.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The research described an application to Atari 2600 gaming.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Other deep reinforcement learning models preceded it.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional deep belief networks (CDBN) have structure very similar to convolutional neural networks and are trained similarly to deep belief networks.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Therefore, they exploit the 2D structure of images, like CNNs do, and make use of pre-training like deep belief networks.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They provide a generic structure that can be used in many image and signal processing tasks.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Benchmark results on standard image datasets like CIFAR have been obtained using CDBNs.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The feed-forward architecture of convolutional neural networks was extended in the neural abstraction pyramid by lateral and feedback connections.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The resulting recurrent convolutional network allows for the flexible incorporation of contextual information to iteratively resolve local ambiguities.
[src:systolic-array/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In contrast to previous models, image-like outputs at the highest resolution were generated, e.g., for semantic segmentation, image reconstruction, and object localization tasks.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] It is also very relevant in many software architectures today including database engine designs and parallel computing frameworks.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] Synchronous dataflow architectures tune to match the workload presented by real-time data path applications such as wire speed packet forwarding.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] Dataflow architectures that are deterministic in nature enable programmers to manage complex tasks such as processor load balancing, synchronization and accesses to common resources.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] Meanwhile, there is a clash of terminology, since the term *dataflow* is used for a subarea of parallel programming: for dataflow programming.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] Hardware architectures for dataflow was a major topic in computer architecture research in the 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] Jack Dennis of MIT pioneered the field of static dataflow architectures while the Manchester Dataflow Machine and MIT Tagged Token architecture were major projects in dynamic dataflow.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] Instructions and their data dependencies proved to be too fine-grained to be effectively distributed in a large network.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] That is, the time for the instructions and tagged results to travel through a large connection network was longer than the time to do many computations.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] Maurice Wilkes wrote in 1995 that "Data flow stands apart as being the most radical of all approaches to parallelism and the one that has been least successful. ...
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] Out-of-order execution (OOE) has become the dominant computing paradigm since the 1990s.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] This paradigm introduced the idea of an *execution window*.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] The *execution window* follows the sequential order of the von Neumann architecture, however within the window, instructions are allowed to be completed in data dependency order.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] This is accomplished in CPUs that dynamically tag the data dependencies of the code in the execution window.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] The logical complexity of dynamically keeping track of the data dependencies, restricts *OOE* CPUs to a small number of execution units (2-6) and limits the execution window sizes to the range of 32 to 200 instructions, much smaller than envisioned for full dataflow machines.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] Designs that use conventional memory addresses as data dependency tags are called static dataflow machines.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] These machines did not allow multiple instances of the same routines to be executed simultaneously because the simple tags could not differentiate between them.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] Designs that use content-addressable memory (CAM) are called dynamic dataflow machines.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] They use tags in memory to facilitate parallelism.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] Normally, in the control flow architecture, compilers analyze program source code for data dependencies between instructions in order to better organize the instruction sequences in the binary output files.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] The instructions are organized sequentially but the dependency information itself is not recorded in the binaries.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] Binaries compiled for a dataflow machine contain this dependency information.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] A dataflow compiler records these dependencies by creating unique tags for each dependency instead of using variable names.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] By giving each dependency a unique tag, it allows the non-dependent code segments in the binary to be executed *out of order* and in parallel.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] Compiler detects the loops, break statements and various programming control syntax for data flow.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] Programs are loaded into the CAM of a dynamic dataflow computer.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] When all of the tagged operands of an instruction become available (that is, output from previous instructions and/or user input), the instruction is marked as ready for execution by an execution unit.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] This is known as *activating* or *firing* the instruction.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] Once an instruction is completed by an execution unit, its output data is sent (with its tag) to the CAM.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] Any instructions that are dependent upon this particular datum (identified by its tag value) are then marked as ready for execution.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] In this way, subsequent instructions are executed in proper order, avoiding race conditions.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] This order may differ from the sequential order envisioned by the human programmer, the programmed order.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] An instruction, along with its required data operands, is transmitted to an execution unit as a packet, also called an *instruction token*.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] Similarly, output data is transmitted back to the CAM as a *data token*.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] The packetization of instructions and results allows for parallel execution of ready instructions on a large scale.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] Dataflow networks deliver the instruction tokens to the execution units and return the data tokens to the CAM.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] In contrast to the conventional von Neumann architecture, data tokens are not permanently stored in memory, rather they are transient messages that only exist when in transit to the instruction storage.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] The programming is solely based on the configuration by the physical interconnection of specialized computing elements, which basically creates a form of a passive dataflow architecture.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] In October 2024, NextSilicon officially announced the launch of its Maverick-2 accelerator, a dataflow chip meant for HPC workloads.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] Since its launch, NextSilicon has partnered with Sandia National Laboratories to install the chip in the Spectra supercomputer.
[src:systolic-array/dataflow-architecture] In July 2025, the startup Efficient Computer was reported to have built a dataflow chip called Electron E1.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] In mathematics, specifically in linear algebra, **matrix multiplication** is a binary operation that produces a matrix from two matrices.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] For matrix multiplication, the number of columns in the first matrix must be equal to the number of rows in the second matrix.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] The resulting matrix, known as the **matrix product**, has the number of rows of the first and the number of columns of the second matrix.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] The product of matrices **A** and **B** is denoted as **AB**.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Matrix multiplication was first described by the French mathematician Jacques Philippe Marie Binet in 1812, to represent the composition of linear maps that are represented by matrices.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Matrix multiplication is thus a basic tool of linear algebra, and as such has numerous applications in many areas of mathematics, as well as in applied mathematics, statistics, physics, economics, and engineering.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Computing matrix products is a central operation in all computational applications of linear algebra.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] This article will use the following notational conventions: matrices are represented by capital letters in bold, e.g.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] **a**; and entries of vectors and matrices are italic (they are numbers from a field), e.g.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Index notation is often the clearest way to express definitions, and is used as standard in the literature.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] The entry in row i, column j of matrix **A** is indicated by (**A**)*ij*, *A**ij* or *a**ij*.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] **A**1, **A**2, is used to select a matrix (not a matrix entry) from a collection of matrices.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] That is, the entry ⁠ $c_{ij}$ ⁠ of the product is obtained by multiplying term-by-term the entries of the ith row of **A** and the jth column of **B**, and summing these n products.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] In other words, ⁠ $c_{ij}$ ⁠ is the dot product of the ith row of **A** and the jth column of **B**.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Thus the product **AB** is defined if and only if the number of columns in **A** equals the number of rows in **B**, in this case *n*.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] In most scenarios, the entries are numbers, but they may be any kind of mathematical objects for which an addition and a multiplication are defined, that are associative, and such that the addition is commutative, and the multiplication is distributive with respect to the addition.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] In particular, the entries may be matrices themselves (see block matrix).
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] One way of looking at this is that the changes from "plain" vector to column vector and back are assumed and left implicit.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Similarly, a vector $\mathbf {x}$ of length n can be viewed as a row vector, corresponding to a $1\times n$ matrix.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] A vector with n components can be represented as a *1* × *n* matrix (a row-vector) or as a *n* × *1* matrix (a column-vector).
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] The matrix multiplication between the column-vector $\mathbf {a}$ and the row-vector $\mathbf {b} ^{\mathrm {T} }$ , also known as outer-product $\mathbf {a} \mathbf {b} ^{\mathrm {T} }$ , will, instead, give a *n* × *n* matrix.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Historically, matrix multiplication has been introduced for facilitating and clarifying computations in linear algebra.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] This strong relationship between matrix multiplication and linear algebra remains fundamental in all mathematics, as well as in physics, chemistry, engineering and computer science.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] If a vector space has a finite basis, its vectors are each uniquely represented by a finite sequence of scalars, called a coordinate vector, whose elements are the coordinates of the vector on the basis.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] These coordinate vectors form another vector space, which is isomorphic to the original vector space.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] A coordinate vector is commonly organized as a column matrix (also called a *column vector*), which is a matrix with only one column.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] So, a column vector represents both a coordinate vector, and a vector of the original vector space.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Using a Cartesian coordinate system in a Euclidean plane, the rotation by an angle $\alpha$ around the origin is a linear map.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] More precisely, ${\begin{bmatrix}x'\\y'\end{bmatrix}}={\begin{bmatrix}\cos \alpha &-\sin \alpha \\\sin \alpha &\cos \alpha \end{bmatrix}}{\begin{bmatrix}x\\y\end{bmatrix}},$ where the source point $(x,y)$ and its image $(x',y')$ are written as column vectors.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] That is, the composition corresponds to the rotation by angle $\alpha +\beta$ , as expected.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] As an example, a fictitious factory uses 4 kinds of basic commodities, $b_{1},b_{2},b_{3},b_{4}$ to produce 3 kinds of intermediate goods, $m_{1},m_{2},m_{3}$ , which in turn are used to produce 3 kinds of final products, $f_{1},f_{2},f_{3}$ .
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] provide the amount of basic commodities needed for a given amount of intermediate goods, and the amount of intermediate goods needed for a given amount of final products, respectively.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] For example, to produce one unit of intermediate good $m_{1}$ , one unit of basic commodity $b_{1}$ , two units of $b_{2}$ , no units of $b_{3}$ , and one unit of $b_{4}$ are needed, corresponding to the first column of $\mathbf {A}$ .
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] this matrix directly provides the amounts of basic commodities needed for given amounts of final goods.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] For example, the bottom left entry of $\mathbf {AB}$ is computed as $1\cdot 1+1\cdot 2+2\cdot 4=11$ , reflecting that $11$ units of $b_{4}$ are needed to produce one unit of $f_{1}$ .
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Indeed, one $b_{4}$ unit is needed for $m_{1}$ , one for each of two $m_{2}$ , and 2 for each of the four $m_{3}$ units that go into the $f_{1}$ unit, see picture.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Similarly, the product matrix $\mathbf {AB}$ can be used to compute the needed amounts of basic goods for other final-good amount data.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] where $\mathbf {x} ^{\mathsf {T}}$ is the row vector obtained by transposing $\mathbf {x}$ .
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] where $\mathbf {x} ^{\dagger }$ denotes the conjugate transpose of $\mathbf {x}$ (conjugate of the transpose, or equivalently transpose of the conjugate).
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Matrix multiplication shares some properties with usual multiplication.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] However, matrix multiplication is not defined if the number of columns of the first factor differs from the number of rows of the second factor, and it is non-commutative, even when the product remains defined after changing the order of the factors.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] If **A** and **B** are matrices of respective sizes ⁠ $m\times n$ ⁠ and ⁠ $p\times q$ ⁠, then $\mathbf {A} \mathbf {B}$ is defined if ⁠ $n=p$ ⁠, and $\mathbf {B} \mathbf {A}$ is defined if ⁠ $m=q$ ⁠.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Therefore, if one of the products is defined, the other one need not be defined.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] If ⁠ $m=q\neq n=p$ ⁠, the two products are defined, but have different sizes; thus they cannot be equal.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Only if ⁠ $m=q=n=p$ ⁠, that is, if **A** and **B** are square matrices of the same size, are both products defined and of the same size.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] If, instead of a field, the entries are supposed to belong to a ring, then one must add the condition that c belongs to the center of the ring.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] One special case where commutativity does occur is when **D** and **E** are two (square) diagonal matrices (of the same size); then **DE** = **ED**.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Again, if the matrices are over a general ring rather than a field, the corresponding entries in each must also commute with each other for this to hold.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] The matrix product is distributive with respect to matrix addition.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] If **A** is a matrix and c a scalar, then the matrices $c\mathbf {A}$ and $\mathbf {A} c$ are obtained by left or right multiplying all entries of **A** by c.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] If the scalars have the commutative property, then all four matrices are equal.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] More generally, all four are equal if *c* belongs to the center of a ring containing the entries of the matrices, because in this case, *c***X** = **X***c* for all matrices **X**.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] If the scalars have the commutative property, the transpose of a product of matrices is the product, in the reverse order, of the transposes of the factors.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] where T denotes the transpose, that is the interchange of rows and columns.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] This identity does not hold for noncommutative entries, since the order between the entries of **A** and **B** is reversed, when one expands the definition of the matrix product.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] where * denotes the entry-wise complex conjugate of a matrix.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] This results from applying to the definition of matrix product the fact that the conjugate of a sum is the sum of the conjugates of the summands and the conjugate of a product is the product of the conjugates of the factors.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Transposition acts on the indices of the entries, while conjugation acts independently on the entries themselves.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] where † denotes the conjugate transpose (conjugate of the transpose, or equivalently transpose of the conjugate).
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] This extends naturally to the product of any number of matrices provided that the dimensions match.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] is defined and does not depend on the order of the multiplications, if the order of the matrices is kept fixed.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] These properties may be proved by straightforward but complicated summation manipulations.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] This result also follows from the fact that matrices represent linear maps.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Therefore, the associative property of matrices is simply a specific case of the associative property of function composition.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Although the result of a sequence of matrix products does not depend on the order of operation (provided that the order of the matrices is not changed), the computational complexity may depend dramatically on this order.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Algorithms have been designed for choosing the best order of products; see Matrix chain multiplication.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Let us denote ${\mathcal {M}}_{n}(R)$ the set of *n*×*n* square matrices with entries in a ring R, which, in practice, is often a field.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] In ${\mathcal {M}}_{n}(R)$ , the product is defined for every pair of matrices.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] This makes ${\mathcal {M}}_{n}(R)$ a ring, which has the identity matrix **I** as an identity element (the matrix whose diagonal entries are equal to 1 and all other entries are 0).
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] This ring is also an associative R-algebra.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] If *n* > 1, many matrices do not have a multiplicative inverse.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] For example, a matrix such that all entries of a row (or a column) are 0 does not have an inverse.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] A matrix that has an inverse is an invertible matrix.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] A product of matrices is invertible if and only if each factor is invertible.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] When R is commutative, and, in particular, when it is a field, the determinant of a product is the product of the determinants.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] The other matrix invariants do not behave as well with products.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Nevertheless, if R is commutative, **AB** and **BA** have the same trace, the same characteristic polynomial, and the same eigenvalues with the same multiplicities.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] However, the eigenvectors are generally different if **AB** ≠ **BA**.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] One may raise a square matrix to any nonnegative integer power multiplying it by itself repeatedly in the same way as for ordinary numbers.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Computing the kth power of a matrix needs *k* – 1 times the time of a single matrix multiplication, if it is done with the trivial algorithm (repeated multiplication).
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] As this may be very time consuming, one generally prefers using exponentiation by squaring, which requires less than 2 log2 *k* matrix multiplications, and is therefore much more efficient.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] An easy case for exponentiation is that of a diagonal matrix.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] The definition of matrix product requires that the entries belong to a semiring, and does not require multiplication of elements of the semiring to be commutative.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] In many applications, the matrix elements belong to a field, although the tropical semiring is also a common choice for graph shortest path problems.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Even in the case of matrices over fields, the product is not commutative in general, although it is associative and is distributive over matrix addition.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] The identity matrices (which are the square matrices whose entries are zero outside of the main diagonal and 1 on the main diagonal) are identity elements of the matrix product.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] It follows that the *n* × *n* matrices over a ring form a ring, which is noncommutative except if *n* = 1 and the ground ring is commutative.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] A square matrix may have a multiplicative inverse, called an inverse matrix.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] In the common case where the entries belong to a commutative ring R, a matrix has an inverse if and only if its determinant has a multiplicative inverse in R.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] The determinant of a product of square matrices is the product of the determinants of the factors.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] The *n* × *n* matrices that have an inverse form a group under matrix multiplication, the subgroups of which are called matrix groups.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Many classical groups (including all finite groups) are isomorphic to matrix groups; this is the starting point of the theory of group representations.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Matrices are the morphisms of a category, the category of matrices.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] The objects are the natural numbers that measure the size of matrices, and the composition of morphisms is matrix multiplication.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] The source of a morphism is the number of columns of the corresponding matrix, and the target is the number of rows.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] The matrix multiplication algorithm that results from the definition requires, in the worst case, ⁠ $n^{3}$ ⁠ multiplications and ⁠ $(n-1)n^{2}$ ⁠ additions of scalars to compute the product of two square *n*×*n* matrices.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Its computational complexity is therefore ⁠ $O(n^{3})$ ⁠, in a model of computation for which the scalar operations take constant time.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] Rather surprisingly, this complexity is not optimal, as shown in 1969 by Volker Strassen, who provided an algorithm, now called Strassen's algorithm, with a complexity of $O(n^{\log _{2}7})\approx O(n^{2.8074}).$ Strassen's algorithm can be parallelized to further improve the performance.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] As of January 2024, the best peer-reviewed matrix multiplication algorithm is by Virginia Vassilevska Williams, Yinzhan Xu, Zixuan Xu, and Renfei Zhou and has complexity *O*(*n*2.371552).
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] It is not known whether matrix multiplication can be performed in *n*2 + o(1) time.
[src:systolic-array/matrix-multiplication] This would be optimal, since one must read the ⁠ $n^{2}$ ⁠ elements of a matrix in order to multiply it with another matrix.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] In computer science, **parallelism** and concurrency are two different things: a parallel program uses multiple CPU cores, each core performing a task independently.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] On the other hand, concurrency enables a program to deal with multiple tasks even on a single CPU core; the core switches between tasks (i.e. threads) without necessarily completing each one.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] A program can have both, neither or a combination of parallelism and concurrency characteristics.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism, with multi-core and multi-processor computers having multiple processing elements within a single machine, while clusters, MPPs, and grids use multiple computers to work on the same task.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Specialized parallel computer architectures are sometimes used alongside traditional processors, for accelerating specific tasks.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Communication and synchronization between the different subtasks are typically some of the greatest obstacles to getting optimal parallel program performance.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] A theoretical upper bound on the speed-up of a single program as a result of parallelization is given by Amdahl's law, which states that it is limited by the fraction of time for which the parallelization can be utilised.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Traditionally, computer software has been written for serial computation.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] To solve a problem, an algorithm is constructed and implemented as a serial stream of instructions.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] These instructions are executed on a central processing unit on one computer.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Only one instruction may execute at a time—after that instruction is finished, the next one is executed.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Parallel computing, on the other hand, uses multiple processing elements simultaneously to solve a problem.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] This is accomplished by breaking the problem into independent parts so that each processing element can execute its part of the algorithm simultaneously with the others.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The processing elements can be diverse and include resources such as a single computer with multiple processors, several networked computers, specialized hardware, or any combination of the above.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Historically parallel computing was used for scientific computing and the simulation of scientific problems, particularly in the natural and engineering sciences, such as meteorology.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] This led to the design of parallel hardware and software, and high performance computing.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Frequency scaling was the dominant reason for improvements in computer performance from the mid-1980s until 2004.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The runtime of a program is equal to the number of instructions multiplied by the average time per instruction.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Maintaining everything else constant, increasing the clock frequency decreases the average time it takes to execute an instruction.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] An increase in frequency thus decreases runtime for all compute-bound programs.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] However, power consumption *P* by a chip is given by the equation *P* = *C* × *V* 2 × *F*, where *C* is the capacitance being switched per clock cycle (proportional to the number of transistors whose inputs change), *V* is voltage, and *F* is the processor frequency (cycles per second).
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Increases in frequency increase the amount of power used in a processor.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Increasing processor power consumption led ultimately to Intel's May 8, 2004 cancellation of its Tejas and Jayhawk processors, which is generally cited as the end of frequency scaling as the dominant computer architecture paradigm.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] To deal with the problem of power consumption and overheating the major central processing unit (CPU or processor) manufacturers started to produce power efficient processors with multiple cores.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The core is the computing unit of the processor and in multi-core processors each core is independent and can access the same memory concurrently.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Multi-core processors have brought parallel computing to desktop computers.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Thus parallelization of serial programs has become a mainstream programming task.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] In 2012 quad-core processors became standard for desktop computers, while servers had 10+ core processors.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Moore's law predicted that the number of cores per processor would double every 18–24 months.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] By 2023 some processors had over one hundred cores.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Some designs having a mix of performance and efficiency cores (such as ARM's big.LITTLE design) due to thermal and design constraints.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] An operating system can ensure that different tasks and user programs are run in parallel on the available cores.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] However, for a serial software program to take full advantage of the multi-core architecture the programmer needs to restructure and parallelize the code.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] A speed-up of application software runtime will no longer be achieved through frequency scaling, instead programmers will need to parallelize their software code to take advantage of the increasing computing power of multicore architectures.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Optimally, the speedup from parallelization would be linear—doubling the number of processing elements should halve the runtime, and doubling it a second time should again halve the runtime.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] However, very few parallel algorithms achieve optimal speedup.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Most of them have a near-linear speedup for small numbers of processing elements, which flattens out into a constant value for large numbers of processing elements.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The maximum potential speedup of an overall system can be calculated by Amdahl's law.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law indicates that optimal performance improvement is achieved by balancing enhancements to both parallelizable and non-parallelizable components of a task.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Furthermore, it reveals that increasing the number of processors yields diminishing returns, with negligible speedup gains beyond a certain point.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law has limitations, including assumptions of fixed workload, neglecting inter-process communication and synchronization overheads, primarily focusing on computational aspect and ignoring extrinsic factors such as data persistence, I/O operations, and memory access overheads.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Gustafson's law and Universal Scalability Law give a more realistic assessment of the parallel performance.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Understanding data dependencies is fundamental in implementing parallel algorithms.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] No program can run more quickly than the longest chain of dependent calculations (known as the critical path), since calculations that depend upon prior calculations in the chain must be executed in order.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] However, most algorithms do not consist of just a long chain of dependent calculations; there are usually opportunities to execute independent calculations in parallel.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Let *P**i* and *P**j* be two program segments.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions describe when the two are independent and can be executed in parallel.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] For *P**i*, let *I**i* be all of the input variables and *O**i* the output variables, and likewise for *P**j*.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Violation of the first condition introduces a flow dependency, corresponding to the first segment producing a result used by the second segment.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The second condition represents an anti-dependency, when the second segment produces a variable needed by the first segment.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The third and final condition represents an output dependency: when two segments write to the same location, the result comes from the logically last executed segment.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] In this example, instruction 3 cannot be executed before (or even in parallel with) instruction 2, because instruction 3 uses a result from instruction 2.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] It violates condition 1, and thus introduces a flow dependency.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] In this example, there are no dependencies between the instructions, so they can all be run in parallel.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions do not allow memory to be shared between different processes.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] For that, some means of enforcing an ordering between accesses is necessary, such as semaphores, barriers or some other synchronization method.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Subtasks in a parallel program are often called threads.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Some parallel computer architectures use smaller, lightweight versions of threads known as fibers, while others use bigger versions known as processes.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] However, "threads" is generally accepted as a generic term for subtasks.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Threads will often need synchronized access to an object or other resource, for example when they must update a variable that is shared between them.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Without synchronization, the instructions between the two threads may be interleaved in any order.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] If instruction 1B is executed between 1A and 3A, or if instruction 1A is executed between 1B and 3B, the program will produce incorrect data.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The programmer must use a lock to provide mutual exclusion.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] A lock is a programming language construct that allows one thread to take control of a variable and prevent other threads from reading or writing it, until that variable is unlocked.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The thread holding the lock is free to execute its critical section (the section of a program that requires exclusive access to some variable), and to unlock the data when it is finished.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] One thread will successfully lock variable V, while the other thread will be locked out—unable to proceed until V is unlocked again.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] This guarantees correct execution of the program.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Locks may be necessary to ensure correct program execution when threads must serialize access to resources, but their use can greatly slow a program and may affect its reliability.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Locking multiple variables using non-atomic locks introduces the possibility of program deadlock.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] An atomic lock locks multiple variables all at once.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] If it cannot lock all of them, it does not lock any of them.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] If two threads each need to lock the same two variables using non-atomic locks, it is possible that one thread will lock one of them and the second thread will lock the second variable.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] In such a case, neither thread can complete, and deadlock results.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Many parallel programs require that their subtasks act in synchrony.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Barriers are typically implemented using a lock or a semaphore.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] One class of algorithms, known as lock-free and wait-free algorithms, altogether avoids the use of locks and barriers.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] However, this approach is generally difficult to implement and requires correctly designed data structures.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Not all parallelization results in speed-up.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Generally, as a task is split up into more and more threads, those threads spend an ever-increasing portion of their time communicating with each other or waiting on each other for access to resources.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Once the overhead from resource contention or communication dominates the time spent on other computation, further parallelization (that is, splitting the workload over even more threads) increases rather than decreases the amount of time required to finish.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] This problem, known as parallel slowdown, can be improved in some cases by software analysis and redesign.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Applications are often classified according to how often their subtasks need to synchronize or communicate with each other.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] An application exhibits fine-grained parallelism if its subtasks must communicate many times per second; it exhibits coarse-grained parallelism if they do not communicate many times per second, and it exhibits embarrassing parallelism if they rarely or never have to communicate.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Embarrassingly parallel applications are considered the easiest to parallelize.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Flynn created one of the earliest classification systems for parallel (and sequential) computers and programs, now known as Flynn's taxonomy.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Flynn classified programs and computers by whether they were operating using a single set or multiple sets of instructions, and whether or not those instructions were using a single set or multiple sets of data.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-single-data (SISD) classification is equivalent to an entirely sequential program.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-multiple-data (SIMD) classification is analogous to doing the same operation repeatedly over a large data set.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] This is commonly done in signal processing applications.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-single-data (MISD) is a rarely used classification.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] While computer architectures to deal with this were devised (such as systolic arrays), few applications that fit this class materialized.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-multiple-data (MIMD) programs are by far the most common type of parallel programs.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Hennessy, "Some machines are hybrids of these categories, of course, but this classic model has survived because it is simple, easy to understand, and gives a good first approximation.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can incur significant overhead in practice, primarily due to the costs associated with merging data from multiple processes.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Specifically, inter-process communication and synchronization can lead to overheads that are substantially higher—often by two or more orders of magnitude—compared to processing the same data on a single thread.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Therefore, the overall improvement should be carefully evaluated.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] From the advent of very-large-scale integration (VLSI) computer-chip fabrication technology in the 1970s until about 1986, speed-up in computer architecture was driven by doubling computer word size—the amount of information the processor can manipulate per cycle.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Increasing the word size reduces the number of instructions the processor must execute to perform an operation on variables whose sizes are greater than the length of the word.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Historically, 4-bit microprocessors were replaced with 8-bit, then 16-bit, then 32-bit microprocessors.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] This trend generally came to an end with the introduction of 32-bit processors, which has been a standard in general-purpose computing for two decades.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Not until the early 2000s, with the advent of x86-64 architectures, did 64-bit processors become commonplace.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] A computer program is, in essence, a stream of instructions executed by a processor.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Without instruction-level parallelism, a processor can only issue less than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC < 1).
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *subscalar* processors.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] These instructions can be re-ordered and combined into groups which are then executed in parallel without changing the result of the program.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] This is known as instruction-level parallelism.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Advances in instruction-level parallelism dominated computer architecture from the mid-1980s until the mid-1990s.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] All modern processors have multi-stage instruction pipelines.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Each stage in the pipeline corresponds to a different action the processor performs on that instruction in that stage; a processor with an *N*-stage pipeline can have up to *N* different instructions at different stages of completion and thus can issue one instruction per clock cycle (IPC = 1).
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *scalar* processors.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The canonical example of a pipelined processor is a RISC processor, with five stages: instruction fetch (IF), instruction decode (ID), execute (EX), memory access (MEM), and register write back (WB).
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The Pentium 4 processor had a 35-stage pipeline.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Most modern processors also have multiple execution units.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] They usually combine this feature with pipelining and thus can issue more than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC > 1).
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *superscalar* processors.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Superscalar processors differ from multi-core processors in that the several execution units are not entire processors (i.e. processing units).
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Instructions can be grouped together only if there is no data dependency between them.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Scoreboarding and the Tomasulo algorithm (which is similar to scoreboarding but makes use of register renaming) are two of the most common techniques for implementing out-of-order execution and instruction-level parallelism.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Task parallelisms is the characteristic of a parallel program that "entirely different calculations can be performed on either the same or different sets of data".
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] This contrasts with data parallelism, where the same calculation is performed on the same or different sets of data.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Task parallelism involves the decomposition of a task into sub-tasks and then allocating each sub-task to a processor for execution.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The processors would then execute these sub-tasks concurrently and often cooperatively.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Task parallelism does not usually scale with the size of a problem.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Superword level parallelism is a vectorization technique based on loop unrolling and basic block vectorization.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] It is distinct from loop vectorization algorithms in that it can exploit parallelism of inline code, such as manipulating coordinates, color channels or in loops unrolled by hand.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Main memory in a parallel computer is either shared memory (shared between all processing elements in a single address space), or distributed memory (in which each processing element has its own local address space).
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Distributed memory refers to the fact that the memory is logically distributed, but often implies that it is physically distributed as well.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Distributed shared memory and memory virtualization combine the two approaches, where the processing element has its own local memory and access to the memory on non-local processors.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Accesses to local memory are typically faster than accesses to non-local memory.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] On the supercomputers, distributed shared memory space can be implemented using the programming model such as PGAS.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] This model allows processes on one compute node to transparently access the remote memory of another compute node.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] All compute nodes are also connected to an external shared memory system via high-speed interconnect, such as Infiniband, this external shared memory system is known as burst buffer, which is typically built from arrays of non-volatile memory physically distributed across multiple I/O nodes.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Computer architectures in which each element of main memory can be accessed with equal latency and bandwidth are known as uniform memory access (UMA) systems.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Typically, that can be achieved only by a shared memory system, in which the memory is not physically distributed.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] A system that does not have this property is known as a non-uniform memory access (NUMA) architecture.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Distributed memory systems have non-uniform memory access.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Computer systems (with the exception of Groq's LPUs) make use of caches—small and fast memories located close to the processor which store temporary copies of memory values (nearby in both the physical and logical sense).
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Parallel computer systems have difficulties with caches that may store the same value in more than one location, with the possibility of incorrect program execution.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] These computers require a cache coherency system, which keeps track of cached values and strategically purges them, thus ensuring correct program execution.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Bus snooping is one of the most common methods for keeping track of which values are being accessed (and thus should be purged).
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Designing large, high-performance cache coherence systems is a very difficult problem in computer architecture.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] As a result, shared memory computer architectures do not scale and distributed memory systems do.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Parallel computers based on interconnected networks need to have some kind of routing to enable the passing of messages between nodes that are not directly connected.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The medium used for communication between the processors is likely to be hierarchical in large multiprocessor machines.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] This classification is broadly analogous to the distance between basic computing nodes.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] These are not mutually exclusive; for example, clusters of symmetric multiprocessors are relatively common.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] A multi-core processor is a processor that includes multiple processing units (called "cores") on the same chip.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] IBM's Cell microprocessor, designed for use in the Sony PlayStation 3, is a prominent multi-core processor.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Each core in a multi-core processor can potentially be superscalar as well—that is, on every clock cycle, each core can issue multiple instructions from one thread.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Simultaneous multithreading (of which Intel's Hyper-Threading is the best known) was an early form of pseudo-multi-coreism.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] A processor capable of concurrent multithreading includes multiple execution units in the same processing unit—that is it has a superscalar architecture—and can issue multiple instructions per clock cycle from *multiple* threads.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Temporal multithreading on the other hand includes a single execution unit in the same processing unit and can issue one instruction at a time from *multiple* threads.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] A symmetric multiprocessor (SMP) is a computer system with multiple identical processors that share memory and connect via a bus.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Bus contention prevents bus architectures from scaling.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] As a result, SMPs generally do not comprise more than 32 processors.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Because of the small size of the processors and the significant reduction in the requirements for bus bandwidth achieved by large caches, such symmetric multiprocessors are extremely cost-effective, provided that a sufficient amount of memory bandwidth exists.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] A distributed computer (also known as a distributed memory multiprocessor) is a distributed memory computer system in which the processing elements are connected by a network.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Distributed computers are highly scalable.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have a lot of overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] A cluster is a group of loosely coupled computers that work together closely, so that in some respects they can be regarded as a single computer.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Clusters are composed of multiple standalone machines connected by a network.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] While machines in a cluster do not have to be symmetric, load balancing is more difficult if they are not.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The most common type of cluster is the Beowulf cluster, which is a cluster implemented on multiple identical commercial off-the-shelf computers connected with a TCP/IP Ethernet local area network.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Beowulf technology was originally developed by Thomas Sterling and Donald Becker.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] 87% of all Top500 supercomputers are clusters.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The remaining are Massively Parallel Processors, explained below.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Because grid computing systems (described below) can easily handle embarrassingly parallel problems, modern clusters are typically designed to handle more difficult problems—problems that require nodes to share intermediate results with each other more often.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] This requires a high bandwidth and, more importantly, a low-latency interconnection network.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Many historic and current supercomputers use customized high-performance network hardware specifically designed for cluster computing, such as the Cray Gemini network.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] As of 2014, most current supercomputers use some off-the-shelf standard network hardware, often Myrinet, InfiniBand, or Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] A massively parallel processor (MPP) is a single computer with many networked processors.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] MPPs have many of the same characteristics as clusters, but MPPs have specialized interconnect networks (whereas clusters use commodity hardware for networking).
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] MPPs also tend to be larger than clusters, typically having "far more" than 100 processors.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] In an MPP, "each CPU contains its own memory and copy of the operating system and application.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] IBM's Blue Gene/L, the fifth fastest supercomputer in the world according to the June 2009 TOP500 ranking, is an MPP.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Grid computing is the most distributed form of parallel computing.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] It makes use of computers communicating over the Internet to work on a given problem.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Because of the low bandwidth and extremely high latency available on the Internet, distributed computing typically deals only with embarrassingly parallel problems.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Most grid computing applications use middleware (software that sits between the operating system and the application to manage network resources and standardize the software interface).
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The most common grid computing middleware is the Berkeley Open Infrastructure for Network Computing (BOINC).
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Often volunteer computing software makes use of "spare cycles", performing computations at times when a computer is idling.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The ubiquity of the Internet and high-bandwidth networks enabled cloud computing, a model where massively parallel resources are provided as a service.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] This paradigm abstracts the underlying hardware, allowing users to access virtualized clusters for scalable workloads without managing physical infrastructure.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Modern distributed ledger protocols apply parallel computing principles to overcome the sequential bottlenecks of traditional blockchains.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] By sharding the state space, newer consensus architectures allow for "massively parallel transaction processing".
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] In this model, utilized by protocols such as Cerberus, independent transactions are treated as parallel tasks that can be executed simultaneously on different nodes, rather than being processed serially in a single global block.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Within parallel computing, there are specialized parallel devices that remain niche areas of interest.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] While not domain-specific, they tend to be applicable to only a few classes of parallel problems.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Reconfigurable computing is the use of a field-programmable gate array (FPGA) as a co-processor to a general-purpose computer.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] An FPGA is, in essence, a computer chip that can rewire itself for a given task.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] FPGAs can be programmed with hardware description languages such as VHDL or Verilog.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Several vendors have created C to HDL languages that attempt to emulate the syntax and semantics of the C programming language, with which most programmers are familiar.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The best known C to HDL languages are Mitrion-C, Impulse C, and Handel-C.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Specific subsets of SystemC based on C++ can also be used for this purpose.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] AMD's decision to open its HyperTransport technology to third-party vendors has become the enabling technology for high-performance reconfigurable computing.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] General-purpose computing on graphics processing units (GPGPU) is a fairly recent trend in computer engineering research.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] GPUs are co-processors that have been heavily optimized for computer graphics processing.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Computer graphics processing is a field dominated by data parallel operations—particularly linear algebra matrix operations.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] In the early days, GPGPU programs used the normal graphics APIs for executing programs.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] However, several new programming languages and platforms have been built to do general purpose computation on GPUs with both Nvidia and AMD releasing programming environments with CUDA and Stream SDK respectively.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Other GPU programming languages include BrookGPU, PeakStream, and RapidMind.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Nvidia has also released specific products for computation in their Tesla series.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The technology consortium Khronos Group has released the OpenCL specification, which is a framework for writing programs that execute across platforms consisting of CPUs and GPUs.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] AMD, Apple, Intel, Nvidia and others are supporting OpenCL.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Several application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) approaches have been devised for dealing with parallel applications.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Because an ASIC is (by definition) specific to a given application, it can be fully optimized for that application.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] As a result, for a given application, an ASIC tends to outperform a general-purpose computer.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] However, ASICs are created by UV photolithography.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] This process requires a mask set, which can be extremely expensive.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] A mask set can cost over a million US dollars.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] (The smaller the transistors required for the chip, the more expensive the mask will be.) Meanwhile, performance increases in general-purpose computing over time (as described by Moore's law) tend to wipe out these gains in only one or two chip generations.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] High initial cost, and the tendency to be overtaken by Moore's-law-driven general-purpose computing, has rendered ASICs unfeasible for most parallel computing applications.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] One example is the PFLOPS RIKEN MDGRAPE-3 machine which uses custom ASICs for molecular dynamics simulation.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] A vector processor is a CPU or computer system that can execute the same instruction on large sets of data.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Vector processors have high-level operations that work on linear arrays of numbers or vectors.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] An example vector operation is *A* = *B* × *C*, where *A*, *B*, and *C* are each 64-element vectors of 64-bit floating-point numbers.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] They are closely related to Flynn's SIMD classification.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Cray computers became famous for their vector-processing computers in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] However, vector processors—both as CPUs and as full computer systems—have generally disappeared.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Modern processor instruction sets do include some vector processing instructions, such as with Freescale Semiconductor's AltiVec and Intel's Streaming SIMD Extensions (SSE).
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Concurrent programming languages, libraries, APIs, and parallel programming models (such as algorithmic skeletons) have been created for programming parallel computers.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] These can generally be divided into classes based on the assumptions they make about the underlying memory architecture—shared memory, distributed memory, or shared distributed memory.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Shared memory programming languages communicate by manipulating shared memory variables.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Distributed memory uses message passing.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] POSIX Threads and OpenMP are two of the most widely used shared memory APIs, whereas Message Passing Interface (MPI) is the most widely used message-passing system API.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] One concept used in programming parallel programs is the future concept, where one part of a program promises to deliver a required datum to another part of a program at some future time.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Efforts to standardize parallel programming include an open standard called OpenHMPP for hybrid multi-core parallel programming.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The OpenHMPP directive-based programming model offers a syntax to efficiently offload computations on hardware accelerators and to optimize data movement to/from the hardware memory using remote procedure calls.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The rise of consumer GPUs has led to support for compute kernels, either in graphics APIs (referred to as compute shaders), in dedicated APIs (such as OpenCL), or in other language extensions.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Automatic parallelization of a sequential program by a compiler is the "holy grail" of parallel computing, especially with the aforementioned limit of processor frequency.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Despite decades of work by compiler researchers, automatic parallelization has had only limited success.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Mainstream parallel programming languages remain either explicitly parallel or (at best) partially implicit, in which a programmer gives the compiler directives for parallelization.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] A few fully implicit parallel programming languages exist—SISAL, Parallel Haskell, SequenceL, SystemC (for FPGAs), Mitrion-C, VHDL, and Verilog.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] As a computer system grows in complexity, the mean time between failures usually decreases.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing is a technique whereby the computer system takes a "snapshot" of the application—a record of all current resource allocations and variable states, akin to a core dump—; this information can be used to restore the program if the computer should fail.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing means that the program has to restart from only its last checkpoint rather than the beginning.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] While checkpointing provides benefits in a variety of situations, it is especially useful in highly parallel systems with a large number of processors used in high performance computing.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] As parallel computers become larger and faster, we are now able to solve problems that had previously taken too long to run.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Fields as varied as bioinformatics (for protein folding and sequence analysis) and economics have taken advantage of parallel computing.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can also be applied to the design of fault-tolerant computer systems, particularly via lockstep systems performing the same operation in parallel.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] This provides redundancy in case one component fails, and also allows automatic error detection and error correction if the results differ.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] These methods can be used to help prevent single-event upsets caused by transient errors.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Although additional measures may be required in embedded or specialized systems, this method can provide a cost-effective approach to achieve n-modular redundancy in commercial off-the-shelf systems.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The origins of true (MIMD) parallelism go back to Luigi Federico Menabrea and his *Sketch of the Analytic Engine Invented by Charles Babbage*.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] In 1957, Compagnie des Machines Bull announced the first computer architecture specifically designed for parallelism, the Gamma 60.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] It utilized a fork-join model and a "Program Distributor" to dispatch and collect data to and from independent processing units connected to a central memory.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] In April 1958, Stanley Gill (Ferranti) discussed parallel programming and the need for branching and waiting.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Also in 1958, IBM researchers John Cocke and Daniel Slotnick discussed the use of parallelism in numerical calculations for the first time.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Burroughs Corporation introduced the D825 in 1962, a four-processor computer that accessed up to 16 memory modules through a crossbar switch.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] In 1967, Amdahl and Slotnick published a debate about the feasibility of parallel processing at American Federation of Information Processing Societies Conference.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] It was during this debate that Amdahl's law was coined to define the limit of speed-up due to parallelism.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] In 1969, Honeywell introduced its first Multics system, a symmetric multiprocessor system capable of running up to eight processors in parallel.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] C.mmp, a multi-processor project at Carnegie Mellon University in the 1970s, was among the first multiprocessors with more than a few processors.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The first bus-connected multiprocessor with snooping caches was the Synapse N+1 in 1984.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] SIMD parallel computers can be traced back to the 1970s.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The motivation behind early SIMD computers was to amortize the gate delay of the processor's control unit over multiple instructions.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] In 1964, Slotnick had proposed building a massively parallel computer for the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] His design was funded by the US Air Force, which was the earliest SIMD parallel-computing effort, ILLIAC IV.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The key to its design was a fairly high parallelism, with up to 256 processors, which allowed the machine to work on large datasets in what would later be known as vector processing.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] However, ILLIAC IV was called "the most infamous of supercomputers", because the project was only one-fourth completed, but took 11 years and cost almost four times the original estimate.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] When it was finally ready to run its first real application in 1976, it was outperformed by existing commercial supercomputers such as the Cray-1.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] In the early 1970s, at the MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, Marvin Minsky and Seymour Papert started developing the *Society of Mind* theory, which views the biological brain as massively parallel computer.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] In 1986, Minsky published *The Society of Mind*, which claims that "mind is formed from many little agents, each mindless by itself".
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] The theory attempts to explain how what we call intelligence could be a product of the interaction of non-intelligent parts.
[src:systolic-array/parallel-computing] Minsky says that the biggest source of ideas about the theory came from his work in trying to create a machine that uses a robotic arm, a video camera, and a computer to build with children's blocks.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] In parallel computer architectures, a **systolic array** is a homogeneous network of tightly coupled data processing units (DPUs) called cells or nodes.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Each node or DPU independently computes a partial result as a function of the data received from its upstream neighbours, stores the result within itself and passes it downstream.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] The principles of systolic-like data flow were first seen in Colossus, which was an early computer used to break German Lorenz ciphers during World War II.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Due to the classified nature of Colossus, they were independently invented by H.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Kung and Charles Leiserson who described arrays for many dense linear algebra computations (matrix product, solving systems of linear equations, LU decomposition, etc.) for banded matrices.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Early applications include computing greatest common divisors of integers and polynomials.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Nowadays, they can be found in NPUs and hardware accelerators based on spatial designs.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] The parallel input data flows through a network of hard-wired processor nodes, which combine, process, merge or sort the input data into a derived result.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Because the wave-like propagation of data through a systolic array resembles the pulse of the human circulatory system, the name *systolic* was coined from medical terminology.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] The name is derived from systole as an analogy to the regular pumping of blood by the heart.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Systolic arrays are often hard-wired for specific operations, such as multiply and accumulate, to perform massively parallel integration, convolution, correlation, matrix multiplication or data sorting tasks.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] They are also used for dynamic programming algorithms, used in DNA and protein sequence analysis.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] A systolic array typically consists of a large monolithic network of primitive computing nodes which can be hardwired or software configured for a specific application.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] The nodes are usually fixed and identical, while the interconnect is programmable.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] The more general **wavefront** processors, by contrast, employ sophisticated and individually programmable nodes which may or may not be monolithic, depending on the array size and design parameters.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] The other distinction is that systolic arrays rely on synchronous data transfers, while wavefront tend to work asynchronously.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] The actual processing within each node may be hard wired or block micro coded, in which case the common node personality can be block programmable.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] The systolic array paradigm with data-streams driven by data counters, is the counterpart of the Von Neumann architecture with instruction-stream driven by a program counter.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Because a systolic array usually sends and receives multiple data streams, and multiple data counters are needed to generate these data streams, it supports data parallelism.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] A major benefit of systolic arrays is that all operand data and partial results are stored within (passing through) the processor array.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] There is no need to access external buses, main memory or internal caches during each operation as is the case with Von Neumann or Harvard sequential machines.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] The sequential limits on parallel performance dictated by Amdahl's Law also do not apply in the same way, because data dependencies are implicitly handled by the programmable node interconnect and there are no sequential steps in managing the highly parallel data flow.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Systolic arrays are therefore extremely good at artificial intelligence, image processing, pattern recognition, computer vision and other tasks that animal brains do particularly well.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Wavefront processors in general can also be very good at machine learning by implementing self configuring neural nets in hardware.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] While systolic arrays are officially classified as MISD, their classification is somewhat problematic.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Because the input is typically a vector of independent values, the systolic array is definitely not SISD.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Since these input values are merged and combined into the result(s) and do not maintain their independence as they would in a SIMD vector processing unit, the array cannot be classified as such.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Consequently, the array cannot be classified as a MIMD either, because MIMD can be viewed as a mere collection of smaller SISD and SIMD machines.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Finally, because the data swarm is transformed as it passes through the array from node to node, the multiple nodes are not operating on the same data, which makes the MISD classification a misnomer.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] The other reason why a systolic array should not qualify as a **MISD** is the same as the one which disqualifies it from the SISD category: The input data is typically a vector not a **s**ingle **d**ata value, although one could argue that any given input vector is a single item of data.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] In spite of all of the above, systolic arrays are often offered as a classic example of MISD architecture in textbooks on parallel computing and in engineering classes.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] If the array is viewed from the outside as atomic it should perhaps be classified as **SFMuDMeR** = single function, multiple data, merged result(s).
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Systolic arrays use a pre-defined computational flow graph that connects their nodes.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Kahn process networks use a similar flow graph, but are distinguished by the nodes working in lock-step in the systolic array: in a Kahn network, there are FIFO queues between each node.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] A systolic array is composed of matrix-like rows of data processing units called cells.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Data processing units (DPUs) are similar to central processing units (CPUs), (except for the usual lack of a program counter, since operation is transport-triggered, i.e., by the arrival of a data object).
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Each cell shares the information with its neighbors immediately after processing.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] The systolic array is often rectangular where data flows across the array between neighbour DPUs, often with different data flowing in different directions.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] The data streams entering and leaving the ports of the array are generated by auto-sequencing memory units, ASMs.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] In embedded systems a data stream may also be input from and/or output to an external source.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] In the example, the green matrix is pre-loaded in the array and can be reused for subsequent multiplications.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] An example of a systolic algorithm might be designed for matrix multiplication.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] One matrix is fed in a row at a time from the top of the array and is passed down the array, the other matrix is fed in a column at a time from the left hand side of the array and passes from left to right.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Dummy values are then passed in until each processor has seen one whole row and one whole column.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] At this point, the result of the multiplication is stored in the array and can now be output a row or a column at a time, flowing down or across the array.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Systolic arrays are arrays of DPUs which are connected to a small number of nearest neighbour DPUs in a mesh-like topology.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] DPUs perform a sequence of operations on data that flows between them.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Because the traditional systolic array synthesis methods have been practiced by algebraic algorithms, only uniform arrays with only linear pipes can be obtained, so that the architectures are the same in all DPUs.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] The consequence is that only applications with regular data dependencies can be implemented on classical systolic arrays.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Like SIMD machines, clocked systolic arrays compute in "lock-step" with each processor undertaking alternate compute | communicate phases.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] But systolic arrays with asynchronous handshake between DPUs are called *wavefront arrays*.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] One well-known systolic array is Carnegie Mellon University's iWarp processor, which has been manufactured by Intel.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] An iWarp system has a linear array processor connected by data buses going in both directions.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Systolic arrays (also known as *wavefront processors*), were first described by H.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Leiserson, who published the first paper describing systolic arrays in 1979.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] However, the first machine known to have used a similar technique was the Colossus Mark II in 1944.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Colossus used parallel shift registers to pulse data, which is functionally similar to a systolic array, but it lacked the interconnected "processing elements" (PEs) that define the 1978 Kung-Leiserson architecture.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] The first machine to be explicitly designed as a systolic array was the WARP computer in 1984.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] A linear systolic array in which the processors are arranged in pairs: one multiplies its input by x and passes the result to the right, the next adds $a_{j}$ and passes the result to the right.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Consider a chain of processing elements (PEs), each performing a multiply-accumulate operation.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] It processes input data ( $x_{i}$ ) and weights ( $w_{i}$ ) systolically, meaning data flows through the array in a regular, rhythmic manner.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] The weights remain stationary within each PE, while the input data and partial sums ( $y_{i}$ ) move in opposite directions.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Similarly, n-dimensional convolution can be computed by an n-dimensional array of PEs.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Many other implementations of the 1D convolutions are available, with different data flows.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] See Figure 12 for an algorithm that performs on-the-fly least-squares using one- and two-dimensional systolic arrays.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Bubble sort is also an example of 1D systolic computation, although it applies N-1 passes for an array of size N.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Each pass systolically moves the maximum element of a subsequence towards its final location in the sorted result.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] And after all the elements are pushed in, the process is reversed with the minimum element in each PE being popped out (or "pushed up"), resulting in the stream of elements coming out sorted in ascending order.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] Sorting input arrays of larger size (N > P) than the number of processing elements (P) is somewhat complex to do efficiently with such a system, but can be realized (by adding an external serial processor) in O(N log N/log P) time.
[src:systolic-array/systolic-array] The serial processor needs to manage a "bucket B-tree", where each node in the B-tree has P "buckets" that are eventually each sorted in O(P) time using the PEs.
